### Describe the problem

Since svelte templates lack a return statement, it can lead to "[arrow code]" which has many levels of indentation. Such code can be hard to reason about.  

[arrow code]: https://blog.codinghorror.com/flattening-arrow-code/

For example, a check like this might require you to add a level of indentation to your entire page:

```
{#if user == null}
    Error: Must be logged in to view this page
{: else}
    <!-- page content here -->
{/if}
```

And the problem gets worse as you have more and more conditions to check. 

For example, if you need to use an `await` block, now you have two levels:

```
{#await foo}
    Waiting ...
{:then loaded}
    {#if loaded.someCondition}
        Error: someCondition happened.
    {:else}
        <!-- possibly large block of code -->
    {/if}
{:catch e}
    <!-- error handling -->
{/await}
```


### Describe the proposed solution

It would be nice if svelte templates had something synonymous to guard clauses in code that would help you: 

* Check for some condition
* Display some error message
* Bail out of the rest of the current template scope.


Something like this:

```
{#guard if !someRequredCondition}
    Error Message
{/guard}

<!-- main template-->
```

Which is just syntax sugar for the equivalent code:
```
{#if !someRequriedCondition}
    Error Message
{:else}
    <!-- main template -->
{/if}
```

When used inside other scopes, the guard would only apply the syntax sugar to the rest of the template in that scope.  So, for example, the `await` example from above would become:

```
{#await foo}
    Waiting ...
{:then loaded}
    {#guard if loaded.someCondition}
        Error: someCondition happened.
    {/guard}
    <!-- possibly large block of code -->
{:catch e}
    <!-- error handling -->
{/await}
```

In templates that need to do lots of checking like this, guard block could save several layers of indentation and really help simplify things.  


### Alternatives considered

I briefly thought about proposing something like {#return} so that you could make any block a guard block, but I don't feel like that maps well to templates. Happy to hear alternative proposals here!

